# Accessibility (Minimum Baseline)

## Meaning / structure

- **Heading levels**: use `h1`‾`h6` in the correct order, and generally keep **one `h1` per page**.
- **Landmarks**: separate major regions using `main`, `nav`, `header`, `footer`, etc.

## Interactions

- For clickable elements, prefer `button` or `a`. Avoid adding only `onClick` to a `div` (if unavoidable, use `role`, keyboard support, and focus handling).
- For forms, connect every input to a `label` (`htmlFor`/`id` or `aria-label`, etc.).

## Keyboard / focus

- Keep **focus order** logical, and consider focus trapping when opening modals/dropdowns.
- Add skip links (or similar mechanisms) when it improves usability.

## Visual

- Do not convey information by color alone (pair with icon/text/patterns).
- Ensure sufficient contrast for body content and button text.

## Tests

- Using role/name-based queries in E2E and Jest (RTL) improves both accessibility and test stability.

## Summary

Use semantic HTML, proper labels/buttons/keyboard support, and do not rely on color alone for meaning.
